  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. Global Regulatory Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations conventions against transnational organized crime\n- International standards for anti-money laundering (AML) compliance\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n- Cross-border investigation protocols\n\n3. Reporting and Compliance Requirements\n- Mandatory suspicious transaction reporting\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Enhanced due diligence for high-risk jurisdictions\n- International banking transparency standards\n\n4. Enforcement Coordination\n- Joint investigative teams\n- Coordinated asset seizure and recovery\n- Sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Prosecution of transnational financial crimes\n\n5. Harmonization of Legal Definitions\n- Standardized definitions of money laundering\n- Consistent criminal liability frameworks\n- Shared understanding of predicate offenses\n- Aligned legal approaches to financial crime\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered system of legal cooperation and enforcement against money laundering.",
